al forms of experiences. He proposes the daring thesis that in their efforts to do so, artists have resorted to gnostic models of consciousness. He argues that the attempt to convey these primordial modes of awareness demands a different conception of artistic meaning from any of those that currently dominate contemporary critical discussion. By reworking theories and speech in highly original ways, Elder formulates this new conception. The works of Brakhage, Artaud, Schneeman, Cohen and others lie naked under Elder’s razor-sharp dissecting knife and he exposes the essence of their work, cutting deeply into the themes and theses from which the works are derived. His remarks on the gaps in contemporary critical practices will likely become the focus of much debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCinéma et artsxCanada. 0aCinémaxHistoire et critiquexCanada. 0aExperimental filmsxHistory and criticismxCanada. 0aExperimental filmszCanadaxHistory and criticism. 0aFilms expérimentauxxHistoire et critiquexCanadaxCanadaxKanada. 0aFine Arts. 0aMotion pictures and the artsxCanada. 0aMotion pictures and the artszCanada. 0aMotion picturesxHistory and criticismxCanada. 0aMotion pictureszCanadaxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictureszCanadaxHistory. 0aMotion pictureszCanada. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm & Media. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920817940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208179423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208179/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-12